to the editor re study sets off debate over mammograms value front page dec 9 though screening is an important tool screening techniques for breast cancer have remained the same for the last 30 years these new studies highlight the truth we do n't know enough about preventing and curing the disease i have introduced legislation along with representative sue myrick republican of north carolina to provide 30 million per year over the next five years to the national institute of environmental health sciences to establish centers across the country to study the link between the environment and breast cancer we are exposed to thousands of toxins every day and we must study how they contribute to the development of breast cancer in the meantime i still believe that women should get annual mammograms after age 40 and perform self examinations early detection still provides the best chance for successful treatment nita m lowey member of congress 18th dist ny washington dec 12 2001

